### 1. One-Line Summary
Tenergy 05 FX provides a plush, highly bouncy feel with an extreme arc for effortless lifting, while Jekyll & Hyde X47.5 offers a firmer, more linear, and stable ESN experience tailored for modern, aggressive power-spin attackers.

### 2. Head-to-Head Breakdown

* **Speed & Gears:**
    * **Low Impact:** Tenergy 05 FX is significantly bouncier with its Spring Sponge catapult effect, providing automatic depth on lighter strokes. Jekyll & Hyde X47.5 is tamer and requires more active input.
    * **Top End:** Jekyll & Hyde X47.5 has a much higher maximum speed and power ceiling. Tenergy 05 FX tends to bottom out and lose energy transfer on extremely hard, aggressive strokes.
    * **Linearity:** Jekyll & Hyde X47.5 is highly linear, outputting exactly the power you put in. Tenergy 05 FX is non-linear, with a strong trampoline effect that activates very quickly.

* **Spin Mechanics:**
    * **Opening Loop:** Tenergy 05 FX shines here, picking up backspin effortlessly due to the soft sponge and grippy topsheet. Jekyll & Hyde X47.5 requires better brushing technique but still offers excellent grip.
    * **Max Spin:** Jekyll & Hyde X47.5 generates slightly more absolute spin on full-power shots because the harder sponge can absorb heavier impacts without collapsing.
    * **Topsheet Grip:** Both feature outstanding grip, but Jekyll & Hyde X47.5 feels slightly more optimized for the modern plastic ball, preventing slippage on fast, glancing contacts.

* **Flight Path (Throw Angle):**
    * **Arc Height:** Tenergy 05 FX has an exceptionally high arc, typical of the 05 series but exaggerated by the soft sponge. Jekyll & Hyde X47.5 has a medium-high, more forward-driving trajectory.
    * **Safety:** Tenergy 05 FX provides massive net clearance, making it very safe for slow, spinny loops. Jekyll & Hyde X47.5 offers safety through predictability and trajectory stability.

* **Feel & Feedback:**
    * **Sensation:** Tenergy 05 FX feels very soft, plush, and springy. Jekyll & Hyde X47.5 feels crisp, medium-hard (47.5 degrees), and solid.
    * **Dwell:** Tenergy 05 FX has longer dwell time on soft to medium impact. Jekyll & Hyde X47.5 grabs the ball firmly but releases it faster on hard swings.

* **Control & Short Game:**
    * **Sensitivity:** Tenergy 05 FX is highly sensitive to incoming spin, requiring careful racket angles. Jekyll & Hyde X47.5 is slightly less reactive, making serve return a bit easier.
    * **Touch Play:** Jekyll & Hyde X47.5 is easier to drop short or push tightly because the sponge does not auto-catapult. Tenergy 05 FX requires very soft hands to avoid popping the ball up.

* **Blocking & Countering:**
    * **Passive Block:** Jekyll & Hyde X47.5 is far superior due to its medium-hard sponge and lower spin sensitivity. Tenergy 05 FX can be wildly bouncy and reactive when passively blocking.
    * **Active Counter:** Jekyll & Hyde X47.5 provides excellent support for counter-looping close to the table. Tenergy 05 FX is prone to bottoming out and flying long when trying to counter heavy topspin.

### 3. The Recommendation

* **Choose Tenergy 05 FX if:** You rely on lifting heavy backspin with minimal physical effort, prefer a very soft and springy feel, play a spin-oriented backhand game, or value a high, forgiving arc over flat-out power.
* **Choose Jekyll & Hyde X47.5 if:** You want a linear, medium-hard rubber with high top-end power, need stability for blocking and serve returns, and possess the technique to actively drive the ball forward in topspin rallies.

